HAFF DISEASE - BRAZIL (02): (BAHIA)
***********************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Thu 9 Feb 2017
From: James M. Wilson <jamesmwilson@unr.edu> [edited]


The 1st report of 'acute myalgia' appeared in early December [2016] with an initial cluster of 4 members of a family (older father, mother, and children, 20 and 14 years old) who presented with acute pain in the trapezoidal area, back, and legs. The pain was severe enough that the mother could not walk. These patients did not exhibit fever, arthralgia, and no respiratory or gastrointestinal (GI) symptoms. Palpation of the muscles elicited pain. Laboratory values of note: extremely elevated CK [creatine kinase] of 70 000 IU/L. 3+ myoglobinuria, and elevated AST (aspartate aminotransferase), ALT (alanine aminotransferase), and LDH (lactate dehydrogenase). Normal WBCs [white blood cells ] with no bands. CRP (c-reactive protein test) was less than 5. Their urine was a "Coca-Cola" color. Blood, urine, and feces were sampled; PCR test results (in Brazil) were negative for DEN [dengue fever], CHIK [chikungunya], Zika, parechovirus, and enteroviruses. It was noted this family consumed 44 pounds of fish per month that was predominantly 2 species of marine fish: yellowtail amberjack (_Seriola lalandi_) and any of the fish in either the Serranidae and/or Gadidae families of fish. All of the family members indicated their symptoms began within 12 hours of the consumption of these fish.

The 2nd cluster was 5 more patients: a father, a mother, their son (who lived in a different house), his wife, and [her father] who all ate the same fish (as mentioned above) together. The presentation was similar to the 1st cluster, and the same samples were collected -- all were negative.

The next cluster was a boyfriend and girlfriend who traveled to the hospital from 40 miles [64.4 km] away after visiting the girlfriend's aunt. The boy and girl were admitted to the hospital and the aunt declined admission. All of them had eaten the same fish as mentioned above.

As of [24 Jan 2017], the case counts stand at 62, 34 of which exhibited myalgia and grossly elevated CK. One patient died, a 65 year old male with significant co-morbidity (cardiac insufficiency). A minority of these patients have reportedly had a fine, very light truncal rash. One patient, a 74 year old woman, ate only 2 fish and was later hospitalized. One patient denied consuming fish but ate a dish that contained byproducts of fish. There was also a physician who had consumed fish and was hospitalized. One patient had a CK of 113 000 IU/L and had acute renal failure but did not require dialysis. There is no report of ICU inundation or high demand for dialysis.

All of the patients who had eaten fish were of 1 of the 2 types of aforementioned marine fish. These patients had bought fish in different markets and consumed them in different locations.

The ongoing hypothesis continues to be Haff disease, with notable exceptions:
- this is the largest documented outbreak of Haff disease in Brazil's history;
- this may be the 1st documented outbreak of Haff disease that involved marine, as opposed to freshwater, fish; and
- the clinical finding of dramatically elevated CK values compared to prior reports of Haff disease (see https://www.cdc.gov/mmWR/preview/mmwrhtml/00056038.htm)

We thank Dr Antonio Bandeira, the physician who reported the 1st couple of case clusters for his generosity in sharing this important information with the international community.

--
James M Wilson V, MD FAAP
M2 Medical Intelligence
Nevada
USA
<jamesmwilson@unr.edu>

[Dr Wilson's summary of the situation is very much appreciated, as Haff disease is always associated with ingestion of certain types of fish, which he clarified. - Mod.TG]

